{"id":"project-LICHEN-voze","title":"enqueue_contacts_empty uses magic number 2 for tx_free check","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshcore/adapter.c
Lines: 136-158 (enqueue_contacts_empty)

The function checks for 2 TX slots:
```c
if (adapter->ops.tx_free(adapter->ops.user_data) < 2U) {
    adapter->stats.enqueue_fail_count++;
    return -ENOMEM;
}
```

Then enqueues exactly 2 frames (start and end). This is correct but uses magic number 2.

However, if either enqueue fails, the function returns early with the error, potentially leaving the protocol in an inconsistent state (start frame sent, end frame not sent).

At line 153-157:
```c
ret = enqueue(adapter, start, sizeof(start));
if (ret < 0) {
    return ret;  // First frame might have been partially sent
}
return enqueue(adapter, end, sizeof(end));
```

If the first enqueue succeeds but the second fails, the receiver sees CONTACTS_START without END_OF_CONTACTS, which could cause it to wait indefinitely for contacts that never arrive.

Consider: atomic operation check should verify both can be sent, and if second fails, no recovery is attempted.","status":"open","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:47:29.48792Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:47:29.487952Z"}

